r\n[caption id=\"attachment_476\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"235\"]<a href=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/675px-Convallaria_majalis_0002.jpg\"><img class=\"  wp-image-476\" src=\"http://www.frenchenglishservices.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/675px-Convallaria_majalis_0002-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"675px-Convallaria_majalis_0002\" width=\"235\" height=\"235\" /></a> <a title=\"&quot;Convallaria majalis 0002&quot; by H. Zell - Own work. Licensed under CC BY-SA 3.0 via Wikimedia Commons -\" href=\"http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Convallaria_majalis_0002.JPG#/media/File:Convallaria_majalis_0002.JPG\" target=\"_blank\">H.Zell</a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Labor Day in France</strong>\r\n\r\nMay 1 is Labor Day or International Workers’ Day in many countries around the globe. In France, May 1 is called La fête du Travail or 1er mai. It’s celebrated with demonstrations and parades organized by workers’ organizations and trade unions aimed at airing the demands of workers and campaigning for their rights.These events can also be used to emphasize present social issues, to fight racism or to campaign for the rights of everyone in general.\r\nAs it’s a public holiday in France, most shops, stores, post offices, banks and businesses are closed on Fête du Travail.\r\n\r\n<strong>History of 1er mai</strong>\r\n\r\nFrance officially introduced the 8-hour working holiday on April 23, 1919. May 1 became the Labor Day in France. It was called International Worker\'s Day (Fête internationale des Travailleurs) during that time. This was later changed into Work and Social Unity Day (Fête du Travail et de la Concorde sociale) during World War II by the Vichy regime. There was no holiday on May 1st between 1944 and 1947. It was officially named Labor Day (La Fête du Travail) on the 29th of April 1948.\r\n\r\n<strong>Public Life</strong>\r\n\r\nOutside of tourist spots every cafes, restaurants, banks, stores, post offices and businesses 